00:22.147 --> 00:25.897
<i>Singin' in the rain
Just singin' in the rain</i>

00:25.943 --> 00:30.239
<i>What a glorious feelin'
We're happy again</i>

00:30.280 --> 00:32.323
<i>We'll walk down the lane</i>

00:32.323 --> 00:34.322
<i>With a happy refrain</i>

00:34.368 --> 00:37.912
<i>And singin'
Just singin' in the rain</i>

01:38.890 --> 01:41.684
<i>This is Dora Bailey,
ladies and gentlemen...</i>

01:41.685 --> 01:45.731
<i>talking to you from the front of
the Chinese Theater in Hollywood.</i>

01:45.772 --> 01:49.272
<i>What a night, ladies and
gentlemen. What a night!</i>

01:49.359 --> 01:53.905
Every star in Hollywood is here to
make Monumental Pictures' premiere...

01:53.947 --> 01:58.993
of <i>The Royal Rascal</i>,
the outstanding event of 1927.

01:58.994 --> 02:01.071
Everyone is
breathlessly awaiting...

02:01.121 --> 02:04.721
the arrival of Lina Lamont
and Don Lockwood.

02:05.292 --> 02:07.119
Look who's arriving now.

02:07.169 --> 02:09.963
It's that famous "zip"
girl of the screen...

02:10.005 --> 02:12.207
the darling of the flapper set...

02:12.257 --> 02:14.425
Zelda Zanders!

02:15.594 --> 02:18.263
Zelda! Zelda!

02:18.555 --> 02:22.760
Her new red-hot pash,
J. Cumberland Spendrill III...

02:22.809 --> 02:26.013
that well-known eligible bachelor.

02:26.063 --> 02:31.394
Zelda's had so much unhappiness,
I hope this time it's really love.

02:32.069 --> 02:36.489
And here comes that
exotic star, Olga Mara!

02:36.490 --> 02:38.699
Ooh.

02:38.700 --> 02:43.622
And her new husband,
the Baron de la Bonnet de la Toulon.

02:43.789 --> 02:48.460
They've been married two months already,
but still as happy as newlyweds.

02:50.045 --> 02:53.624
Well, well, well. It's Cosmo Brown!

03:00.347 --> 03:02.265
Cosmo is Don's best friend.

03:02.307 --> 03:04.805
He plays the piano on the
set for Don and Lina...

03:04.851 --> 03:08.521
to get them into those
romantic moods!

03:08.730 --> 03:10.932
Oh, folks, this is it. This is it!

03:17.989 --> 03:22.319
The stars of tonight's picture,
those romantic lovers of the screen...

03:22.369 --> 03:25.163
Don Lockwood and Lina Lamont!

03:30.961 --> 03:34.586
Ladies and gentlemen, when you
look at this gorgeous couple...

03:34.631 --> 03:38.335
it's no wonder they're a household
name all over the world.

03:38.343 --> 03:40.671
Like "bacon and eggs."

03:41.346 --> 03:44.174
"Lockwood and Lamont."

03:46.476 --> 03:49.894
Don, tell me confidentially,
are these rumors true...

03:49.895 --> 03:52.724
that wedding bells are soon
to ring for you and Lina?

03:52.774 --> 03:56.067
Lina and I have no statement
to make at the present time.

03:56.068 --> 03:57.521
We're just good friends.

03:57.529 --> 04:01.734
You've come a long way together.
Won't you tell us how it happened?

04:01.783 --> 04:05.201
Lina and I have made a number
of pictures together...

04:05.202 --> 04:08.828
Oh, no, no, Don. I want your
story from the beginning.

04:08.874 --> 04:11.998
Dora, not in front
of all these people!

04:15.380 --> 04:18.208
The story of your success
is an inspiration...

04:18.257 --> 04:20.711
to young people all over the world.

04:20.927 --> 04:22.344
Please!

04:25.766 --> 04:28.515
Well, to begin with,
any story of my career...

04:28.560 --> 04:32.560
would have to include my
lifelong friend, Cosmo Brown.

04:32.564 --> 04:35.566
We were kids together, grew
up together, worked together.

04:35.567 --> 04:36.768
Yes?

04:37.402 --> 04:42.529
Well, Dora, I've had one motto
which I've always lived by:

04:42.949 --> 04:46.073
"Dignity. Always dignity."

04:46.536 --> 04:50.912
This was instilled in me by Mum
and Dad from the very beginning.

04:50.957 --> 04:54.411
They sent me to the finest
schools, including dancing school.

04:54.419 --> 04:56.747
That's where I first met Cosmo.

04:56.797 --> 05:01.252
And with him, I used to perform for
Mum and Dad's society friends.

05:08.725 --> 05:11.599
<i>They used to make
such a fuss over me.</i>

05:11.645 --> 05:16.601
<i>If I was very good, I was allowed to
accompany Mum and Dad to the theater.</i>

05:16.650 --> 05:18.852
<i>They brought me up on Shaw...</i>

05:18.902 --> 05:21.901
<i>Molière, the finest
of the classics.</i>

05:23.240 --> 05:26.284
To this was added rigorous
musical training...

05:26.285 --> 05:28.657
at the Conservatory of Fine Arts.

05:33.750 --> 05:38.330
<i>We rounded out our apprenticeship
at an exclusive dramatics academy.</i>

05:39.381 --> 05:41.379
<i>And at all times...</i>

05:41.424 --> 05:43.297
<i>the motto remained...</i>

05:43.593 --> 05:44.840
<i>"...Dignity."</i>

05:44.886 --> 05:47.009
<i>"Always dignity."</i>

05:48.974 --> 05:53.054
<i>In a few years, we were ready to
embark on a dance concert tour.</i>

05:53.770 --> 05:57.395
<i>We played the finest symphonic
halls in the country.</i>

05:58.191 --> 06:00.151
<i>Fit as a fiddle
And ready for love</i>

06:00.193 --> 06:02.736
<i>I can jump over
The moon up above</i>

06:02.737 --> 06:05.531
<i>Fit as a fiddle
And ready for love</i>

06:06.908 --> 06:08.906
<i>Haven't a worry
Haven't a care</i>

06:08.952 --> 06:11.371
<i>Feelin' like a feather
That's floatin' on air</i>

06:11.372 --> 06:14.324
<i>Fit as a fiddle
And ready for love</i>

06:15.166 --> 06:19.667
<i>Soon the church bells will be ringin'
And a march with Ma and Pa</i>

06:19.713 --> 06:21.881
<i>How the church bells
will be ringin'</i>

06:21.923 --> 06:24.626
<i>With a hey-nonny-nonny
And a hot-cha-cha</i>

06:24.634 --> 06:26.677
<i>Hi diddle diddle
My baby's okay</i>

06:26.720 --> 06:29.218
<i>Ask me a riddle
I'm happy to say</i>

06:29.222 --> 06:32.175
<i>Fit as a fiddle
And ready for love</i>

07:30.325 --> 07:32.868
<i>Audiences everywhere adored us.</i>

07:32.869 --> 07:34.070
Get out of here!

07:35.288 --> 07:38.617
<i>Finally we decided to
come to sunny California.</i>

07:39.209 --> 07:42.162
<i>We were stranded... We were
staying here, resting up...</i>

07:42.212 --> 07:45.507
<i>when offers from the movie
studios started pouring in.</i>

07:45.548 --> 07:50.128
<i>We sorted them out and decided
to favor Monumental Pictures.</i>

07:50.345 --> 07:54.013
Lina, you hate him. Resist him.
Keep that mood music going.

07:54.014 --> 07:56.513
Now, Phil, you come in.
Keep on grinding.

07:56.559 --> 08:01.310
Now you see her. Now here's the bit,
Bert, where you get it on the jaw.

08:01.982 --> 08:03.183
Cut!

08:03.233 --> 08:05.310
No, no! That wasn't right!

08:05.360 --> 08:09.861
You were supposed to go over the bar and
crash into the glasses! Try it again!

08:09.864 --> 08:11.941
Okay, Bert? Bert!

08:11.992 --> 08:14.240
Oh, that's swell, just swell.

08:14.244 --> 08:16.412
Take him away, fellas!

08:16.413 --> 08:20.334
You'll be all right. We've lost
more stuntmen on these pictures...

08:20.375 --> 08:23.419
It'll take hours to get a new
one from Central Casting.

08:23.420 --> 08:25.622
Mr. Dexter, I can do that.

08:25.672 --> 08:28.625
- You? You're a musician.
- That's a moot point.

08:28.633 --> 08:30.631
No kidding! What's your name?

08:30.677 --> 08:33.471
Don Lockwood, but the
fellas call me "Donald."

08:33.513 --> 08:36.386
Wise guy, huh? Okay. I'll try you.

08:36.433 --> 08:38.475
Get this guy into Bert's suit!

08:38.476 --> 08:43.273
And remember, Lockwood, you might
be trading that fiddle in for a harp.

08:45.275 --> 08:46.567
Camera!

08:47.402 --> 08:50.321
Phil, come in. Now you
see him. That's it.

08:50.363 --> 08:53.032
Now, here's where you
get it right on the jaw.

08:54.826 --> 08:56.027
Cut!

08:56.036 --> 08:57.704
That was wonderful!

08:59.289 --> 09:01.617
Got any more little
chores you want done?

09:01.666 --> 09:02.992
Plenty!

09:07.172 --> 09:08.624
Okay.

09:28.985 --> 09:32.529
<i>My roles in these
films were urbane...</i>

09:32.530 --> 09:34.073
<i>sophisticated...</i>

09:34.074 --> 09:35.275
<i>suave.</i>

09:38.036 --> 09:41.035
And of course, all through
those pictures...

09:41.039 --> 09:44.708
Lina was, as always,
an inspiration to me.

09:44.709 --> 09:46.661
Warm and helpful.

09:46.836 --> 09:48.663
A real lady.

09:52.425 --> 09:56.050
Hello, Miss Lamont. I'm Don
Lockwood, the stuntman.

09:57.972 --> 10:00.800
It was a thrill working
with you, Miss Lamont.

10:00.850 --> 10:02.267
Hey, Don.

10:02.435 --> 10:05.388
Meet the producer of the
picture, R.F. Simpson.

10:05.396 --> 10:09.396
I just saw some rushes and asked
Dexter who the stuntmen were.

10:09.442 --> 10:13.863
He said they were all you. I'm putting
you and Lina together in a picture.

10:13.905 --> 10:16.483
Come to my office.
We'll discuss a contract.

10:16.533 --> 10:18.485
Thanks, Mr. Simpson!

10:22.247 --> 10:25.417
Are you doing anything
tonight, Miss Lamont?

10:26.876 --> 10:28.544
That's funny.

10:28.545 --> 10:30.088
I'm busy.

10:35.051 --> 10:39.427
<i>Lina and I have had the same
wonderful relationship ever since.</i>

10:39.556 --> 10:43.602
But most important of all,
I continue living up to my motto:

10:43.935 --> 10:45.261
"Dignity.

10:45.478 --> 10:47.680
Always dignity."

10:49.065 --> 10:50.266
Thank you, Don.

10:50.316 --> 10:55.022
And I'm sure you and Lina will continue
making movie history tonight...

10:55.071 --> 11:00.027
in your greatest picture,
<i>The Royal Rascal.</i>

11:03.621 --> 11:05.164
Get enough, boys?

11:42.368 --> 11:44.286
She's so refined...

11:44.329 --> 11:46.873
I think I'll kill myself.

12:25.787 --> 12:30.208
Thank you, ladies and gentlemen.
Thank you, thank you, thank you.

12:32.001 --> 12:35.375
We're thrilled at your
response to <i>The Royal Rascal.</i>

12:35.421 --> 12:39.922
We had fun making it, and we hope
you had fun seeing it tonight.

12:42.637 --> 12:47.138
We screen actors aren't much
good at speaking in public.

12:47.183 --> 12:49.727
So we'll just act out our thanks.

13:00.154 --> 13:03.324
- Hot diggity! It's a smash!
- Don, Lina, you were gorgeous!

13:03.366 --> 13:04.709
Lina, you looked pretty
good for a girl.

13:04.810 --> 13:07.362
For heaven's sake!
What's the big idea?

13:07.412 --> 13:11.537
Can't a girl get a word in edgewise?
They're my public too!

13:11.582 --> 13:13.284
The publicity department...

13:13.293 --> 13:17.129
thought it'd be better if Don made
all the speeches for the team.

13:17.130 --> 13:18.331
Why?

13:18.339 --> 13:21.668
You're beautiful. Audiences
think you got a voice to match.

13:21.676 --> 13:24.755
We gotta keep our stars from
looking ridiculous at any cost.

13:24.804 --> 13:27.445
- No one's got that much money.
- What's wrong with the way I talk?

13:28.309 --> 13:31.877
What's the big idea?
Am I dumb or something?

13:32.478 --> 13:35.648
No, it's just that Don's had
so much more experience...

13:35.690 --> 13:39.360
Next time, write me out
a speech. I could memorize it.

13:39.402 --> 13:42.776
Sure. Why don't you recite
the Gettysburg Address?

13:42.780 --> 13:47.531
What do you know about it,
you piano player? Are you anybody?

13:47.577 --> 13:51.998
Donnie, how can you let him talk
to me like that, your fiancée?

13:52.081 --> 13:53.578
My fia...

13:53.833 --> 13:57.412
Lina, you've been reading
those fan magazines again.

13:57.462 --> 14:00.836
Look, you shouldn't believe
all that banana oil...

14:00.840 --> 14:03.213
that Dora Bailey dishes out.

14:03.217 --> 14:07.422
Now, try to get this straight:
There is nothing between us.

14:07.472 --> 14:10.221
There has never been
anything between us.

14:10.224 --> 14:13.678
- Just air.
- Oh, Donnie, you don't mean that.

14:13.728 --> 14:15.851
We'll be late for R.F.'s party.

14:15.897 --> 14:19.727
Better go in separate cars to break
up the mobs. Come on, honey.

14:19.734 --> 14:22.687
Ta-ta, Donnie! See you there!

14:23.780 --> 14:24.981
"Donnie."

14:25.281 --> 14:27.824
Can't that girl take a gentle hint?

14:27.825 --> 14:31.325
Haven't you heard? She's
irresistible. She told me so.

14:31.371 --> 14:34.871
I can't get her out of my hair.
This romance for publicity...

14:34.916 --> 14:37.585
The price of fame.
You've got the glory.

14:37.627 --> 14:39.628
The little heartaches go with it.

14:39.629 --> 14:43.629
Look at me. I got no glory.
I got no fame. I got no mansions.

14:43.674 --> 14:46.377
I got no money. But I've got...

14:46.636 --> 14:49.055
- What have I got?
- I don't know.

14:49.138 --> 14:50.885
I gotta get out of here.

14:59.440 --> 15:01.859
Don't tell me. It's a flat tire.

15:01.901 --> 15:05.275
This car hasn't given me
trouble in nearly six hours.

15:05.279 --> 15:07.152
Hey, there's Don Lockwood!

15:07.740 --> 15:09.283
Hey, give me an autograph!

15:09.325 --> 15:12.904
- Give me your autograph!
- I want a souvenir!

15:12.954 --> 15:14.781
I want a souvenir too!

15:14.831 --> 15:18.376
Hey! You're playing rough here!
You're tearing my...!

15:18.709 --> 15:21.458
Hey, Cos, do something!
Call me a cab!

15:21.462 --> 15:22.788
You're a cab.

15:23.256 --> 15:24.878
Thanks a lot!

15:39.188 --> 15:40.890
- Lady, keep driving.
- Get out!

15:40.898 --> 15:43.817
- Everything's all right!
- I'll call a policeman!

15:43.818 --> 15:45.734
- Just a few blocks.
- Don't hurt me!

15:45.735 --> 15:48.155
- I'm not a criminal.
- I don't care...

15:48.197 --> 15:51.992
You are a criminal! I've seen
that face. You're a gangster!

15:51.993 --> 15:55.579
I've seen your picture in the
paper or in the post office.

15:55.580 --> 15:56.827
Officer!

15:56.831 --> 16:00.956
- This man jumped in my car and...
- Why, it's Don Lockwood!

16:01.002 --> 16:03.921
- Don Lockwood?
- How are you? Out for a joy ride?

16:03.963 --> 16:07.463
Just a lift. My car broke down.
I got surrounded by...

16:07.508 --> 16:10.336
- You're a lucky lady. Anything wrong?
- Why, no.

16:10.344 --> 16:12.467
No, I should think not. Good night.

16:12.513 --> 16:14.340
Good night, officer.

16:15.558 --> 16:19.763
Well, thanks for saving
my life. I'll get out now.

16:19.770 --> 16:22.938
I'm driving to Beverly Hills.
Can I drop you someplace?

16:22.939 --> 16:27.646
I'd like to get out of this suit if
you're going by Camden and Sunset.

16:27.653 --> 16:29.275
Yes, I am.

16:33.034 --> 16:36.329
I'd like to know whose
hospitality I'm enjoying.

16:36.370 --> 16:38.322
Selden. Kathy Selden.

16:38.372 --> 16:40.540
Enchanted, Miss Selden.

16:40.625 --> 16:42.667
I'm sorry I frightened you.

16:42.668 --> 16:46.122
I was getting a little too
much love from my fans.

16:46.172 --> 16:49.046
Oh, that's what you
were running away from.

16:49.091 --> 16:52.261
They did that to you?
That's terrible!

16:55.264 --> 16:57.592
Yes. Yes, it is, isn't it?

16:57.642 --> 16:59.344
It is terrible.

16:59.852 --> 17:02.805
Well, we movie stars
get the glory...

17:02.813 --> 17:06.643
I guess we have to take the little
heartaches that go with it.

17:06.943 --> 17:11.068
People think we lead lives
of glamour and romance...

17:11.113 --> 17:13.156
but we're really lonely.

17:14.200 --> 17:15.696
Terribly lonely.

17:15.701 --> 17:20.496
I really can't tell you how sorry
I am about taking you for a criminal.

17:20.497 --> 17:24.794
But it was understandable, under the
circumstances. I knew I'd seen you.

17:24.795 --> 17:27.462
Which of my pictures have you seen?

17:27.463 --> 17:28.755
I don't remember.

17:28.798 --> 17:30.750
I saw one once.

17:31.342 --> 17:34.295
- You saw one once?
- I think you were dueling.

17:34.345 --> 17:36.513
And there was a girl. Lina Lamont.

17:36.556 --> 17:38.554
I don't go to the movies much.

17:38.558 --> 17:41.853
If you've seen one,
you've seen them all.

17:42.812 --> 17:44.013
Thank you.

17:44.063 --> 17:45.435
No offense.

17:45.481 --> 17:47.775
Movies are entertaining
for the masses...

17:47.817 --> 17:51.066
but the personalities on the
screen don't impress me.

17:51.112 --> 17:54.942
They don't talk or act.
They just make a lot of dumb show.

17:54.991 --> 17:56.613
Well, you know.

17:58.160 --> 17:59.361
Like that.

17:59.870 --> 18:02.072
You mean, like what I do.

18:02.623 --> 18:04.166
Well, yes.

18:04.375 --> 18:07.328
Here we are, Sunset and Camden.

18:08.963 --> 18:11.586
Wait, you mean I'm not an actor?

18:11.591 --> 18:14.260
- Pantomime isn't acting?
- Of course not.

18:14.343 --> 18:18.013
Acting means great parts,
wonderful lines, glorious words.

18:18.014 --> 18:19.431
Shakespeare. Ibsen.

18:19.473 --> 18:21.550
What's your lofty
mission in life...

18:21.601 --> 18:25.101
that lets you sneer at
my humble profession?

18:25.104 --> 18:27.056
I'm an actress. On the stage.

18:27.064 --> 18:28.811
Oh, on the stage.

18:28.858 --> 18:31.436
I'd like to see you.
What're you in now?

18:31.485 --> 18:34.905
I could brush up on my English
or bring an interpreter.

18:35.114 --> 18:36.987
That's if they'd let
in a movie actor.

18:37.033 --> 18:40.075
I'm not in a play now.
But I'm going to New York...

18:40.076 --> 18:44.657
You're going to New York, and someday
we'll all hear of you, won't we?

18:44.665 --> 18:48.244
Kathy Selden as Juliet,
as Lady Macbeth, as King Lear!

18:48.294 --> 18:49.871
You'll have to wear a beard!

18:49.920 --> 18:53.590
Laugh if you want, but the stage
is a dignified profession.

18:53.591 --> 18:55.714
Why are you so conceited?

18:55.760 --> 19:00.010
You're nothing but a shadow on film.
You're not flesh and blood.

19:00.014 --> 19:02.637
- Stop!
- What can I do? I'm only a shadow.

19:02.642 --> 19:06.767
Keep away from me! Just because
you're a big movie star...

19:06.812 --> 19:10.731
you expect every girl to faint
at your feet. Don't touch me!

19:10.732 --> 19:13.436
Fear not, sweet lady.
I will not molest you.

19:13.486 --> 19:18.658
I am but a humble jester. And you?
You are too far above me.

19:18.949 --> 19:20.947
Farewell, Ethel Barrymore.

19:20.993 --> 19:24.288
I must tear myself from your side.

19:36.133 --> 19:40.258
Is this R.F. Simpson's house?
I'm one of the Coconut Grove girls.

19:40.304 --> 19:44.725
- Yes, the floor show. Around the back.
- Oh, I see. Thank you.

20:07.707 --> 20:10.285
- Nice little party, R.F.
- Thanks, Roscoe.

20:10.334 --> 20:13.538
Do you really think you
can get me in the movies?

20:13.587 --> 20:15.789
- I should think so.
- Really?

20:15.840 --> 20:19.670
- The picture's great.
- There's Don. I loved the picture.

20:19.760 --> 20:23.339
- Did you come by way of Australia?
- Hello, Cos. Excuse me.

20:23.389 --> 20:26.468
Cos, tell me the truth.
Am I a good actor?

20:26.517 --> 20:29.345
As long as I work for Monumental,
you're the greatest.

20:29.353 --> 20:31.931
No kidding. You're my pal.
You can tell me.

20:31.981 --> 20:34.354
What's the matter?
Of course, you're good.

20:34.358 --> 20:38.313
Keep telling me from time
to time. I feel a little shaken.

20:38.362 --> 20:40.064
- The new Don Lockwood.
- Don!

20:40.489 --> 20:43.863
- Hi, R.F.
- It's colossal. Where have you been?

20:43.909 --> 20:46.745
There you are. Where were you?
I was lonely.

20:46.746 --> 20:47.947
Hello, Lina.

20:47.997 --> 20:49.699
Okay, fellas. Hold it.

20:50.833 --> 20:53.626
Together again, my two
little stars, Don and Lina.

20:53.627 --> 20:56.046
No kidding, folks,
aren't they great?

20:58.340 --> 21:00.463
All right, open that screen.

21:01.010 --> 21:04.803
- A movie? We just saw one.
- Gotta show one at a party. It's a law.

21:04.804 --> 21:07.724
Everybody, I've got a
few surprises for you.

21:07.725 --> 21:10.098
All right, sit down, sit down.

21:10.186 --> 21:11.933
This'll make you laugh.

21:12.021 --> 21:15.521
There's a madman coming into
my office for months, and...

21:15.649 --> 21:18.568
- You got that gadget working?
- All set.

21:18.569 --> 21:20.646
Okay, let her go.

21:26.368 --> 21:28.036
<i>Hello.</i>

21:28.454 --> 21:33.000
<i>This is a demonstration
of a talking picture.</i>

21:33.209 --> 21:38.254
<i>Notice, it is a picture
of me and I am talking.</i>

21:38.255 --> 21:42.631
<i>Note how my lips and the
sound issuing from them...</i>

21:42.635 --> 21:45.304
<i>are synchronized together...</i>

21:45.346 --> 21:48.299
<i>in perfect unison.</i>

21:48.891 --> 21:52.059
- Who's that?
- Somebody's talking behind that screen.

21:52.060 --> 21:54.639
Come out from behind
that screen, Mr. Simpson.

21:54.730 --> 21:56.523
Oh, no. I'm right here.

21:59.318 --> 22:03.068
<i>My voice has been
recorded on a record.</i>

22:03.155 --> 22:05.357
<i>A talking picture.</i>

22:05.783 --> 22:07.405
<i>Thank you.</i>

22:07.451 --> 22:08.777
<i>Goodbye.</i>

22:12.206 --> 22:13.407
Well?

22:13.749 --> 22:16.498
- It's just a toy.
- It's a scream!

22:16.585 --> 22:19.709
- It's vulgar.
- You think they'll ever use it?

22:19.755 --> 22:23.924
I doubt it. Warners is making a
picture with it, <i>The Jazz Singer.</i>

22:23.925 --> 22:27.426
- They'll lose their shirts.
- It'll never amount to a thing.

22:27.429 --> 22:29.427
They said that about the
horseless carriage.

22:29.431 --> 22:31.804
Let's get on with the show.
Okay, boys.

22:31.851 --> 22:34.053
Come on, my little starlets.

22:34.270 --> 22:36.812
I have a surprise.
A very special cake.

22:36.813 --> 22:39.688
I want you kiddies to
have the first piece.

22:44.989 --> 22:48.159
Well! If it isn't Ethel Barrymore!

22:53.789 --> 22:59.120
I do hope you'll favor us with something
special. Say, Hamlet's soliloquy...

22:59.128 --> 23:02.457
or a scene from Romeo
and Juliet? Don't be shy.

23:02.506 --> 23:06.586
You make about the prettiest
Juliet I've ever seen. Really.

23:09.722 --> 23:13.347
<i>All I do is dream of you
The whole night through</i>

23:13.767 --> 23:17.562
<i>With the dawn I still go on
Dreaming of you</i>

23:17.646 --> 23:19.974
<i>You're every thought
You're everything</i>

23:20.024 --> 23:21.646
<i>You're every song I ever sing</i>

23:21.692 --> 23:25.567
<i>Summer, winter, autumn and spring</i>

23:25.571 --> 23:29.571
<i>And were there more than
Twenty-four hours a day</i>

23:29.825 --> 23:33.495
<i>They'd be spent in sweet content
Dreaming away</i>

23:33.704 --> 23:35.872
<i>When skies are gray
When skies are blue</i>

23:35.873 --> 23:37.871
<i>Morning, noon and nighttime too</i>

23:37.875 --> 23:42.080
<i>All I do the whole day through
Is dream of you</i>

24:04.109 --> 24:05.902
<i>It's the cat's meow!</i>

24:09.239 --> 24:13.285
<i>All I do the whole day through
Is dream of you</i>

24:13.369 --> 24:16.038
- I had to tell you how good you were.
- Excuse me.

24:16.080 --> 24:19.705
Now that I know where you live,
I'd like to see you home.

24:19.750 --> 24:23.420
- Listen, Mr. Lockwood...
- Say, who is this dame anyway?

24:23.421 --> 24:26.464
Someone lofty and far above us all.

24:26.465 --> 24:31.045
She couldn't learn anything from
the movies. She's a stage actress.

24:31.095 --> 24:34.424
Here's one thing I've
learned from the movies!

24:38.435 --> 24:41.479
- I'll kill her!
- Lina, she was aiming at me!

24:41.522 --> 24:44.225
- You never looked lovelier.
- It was an accident.

24:44.274 --> 24:46.522
It happens to me five
or six times a day.

24:46.568 --> 24:48.020
Where is she?

24:48.654 --> 24:49.946
Donnie?

24:52.741 --> 24:55.035
Excuse me. Where'd Miss Selden go?

24:55.077 --> 24:58.827
She grabbed her things and
bolted. Anything I can do?

24:58.872 --> 25:01.700
Sorry. I don't have
time to find out.

25:04.753 --> 25:05.954
Kathy!

25:05.963 --> 25:07.460
Hey, Kathy!

25:09.425 --> 25:10.797
Hey!

25:36.827 --> 25:39.871
Keep that action going.
More steam in the kettle!

25:39.913 --> 25:42.286
More action, boys.
A little more rhythm.

25:42.332 --> 25:44.250
More steam and more water.

25:44.501 --> 25:46.248
- Hi, Maxie.
- Hi, Don.

25:47.212 --> 25:49.164
- Good morning, fellas.
- Hiya, Don.

25:49.214 --> 25:51.132
Did you read Variety today?

25:51.133 --> 25:55.088
"First talking picture, The Jazz Singer.
All-time smash end of first week."

25:55.095 --> 25:58.265
- All-time flop end of the second.
- We start today.

25:58.307 --> 25:59.599
- Good luck.
- Thanks.

25:59.641 --> 26:03.436
I'm now Count Pierre de Bataille,
known as the Duelling Cavalier.

26:03.479 --> 26:06.273
- What's it about?
- It's a French Revolution story.

26:06.315 --> 26:08.233
You're a French aristocrat.

26:08.317 --> 26:11.896
She's a simple girl of the people
and won't even give you a tumble.

26:11.904 --> 26:13.947
Well, it's a living.

26:14.615 --> 26:16.032
Good morning.

26:16.617 --> 26:18.785
Keep the background moving.
Hit him.

26:18.827 --> 26:20.368
Come on. Knock him down!

26:20.369 --> 26:23.119
Get up there and hit
him again. Hurry up!

26:23.165 --> 26:26.665
Why bother to shoot this? Release
the old one under a new title.

26:26.710 --> 26:29.212
You've seen one,
you've seen them all.

26:29.213 --> 26:31.541
- Why'd you say that?
- What's the matter?

26:31.548 --> 26:34.547
That's what that Kathy Selden
said to me that night.

26:34.551 --> 26:37.925
That's three weeks ago.
You still thinking about that?

26:38.097 --> 26:41.801
- I can't get her out of my mind.
- How could you?

26:41.850 --> 26:45.270
She's the first dame who hasn't
fallen for you since you were 4.

26:45.354 --> 26:46.897
She's on my conscience.

26:46.939 --> 26:48.980
It's not your fault
she lost her job.

26:48.981 --> 26:51.480
- I've got to find her.
- You've been trying to.

26:51.485 --> 26:53.983
Short of sending out
bloodhounds and a posse.

26:54.029 --> 26:55.776
Come on, now. Snap out of it.

26:55.864 --> 26:57.782
You can't let this get you down.

26:57.866 --> 27:01.409
You're Donald Lockwood. Donald
Lockwood's an actor, isn't he?

27:01.410 --> 27:03.488
What's the first thing
an actor learns?

27:03.497 --> 27:08.828
"The show must go on, come rain,
come shine, come snow, come sleet!"

27:12.756 --> 27:14.003
Yeah.

27:14.258 --> 27:16.335
<i>The world's so full
